# AIMD Adaptive Concurrency Demo
# REST Client format for VS Code REST Client plugin
#
# This demo shows AIMD (Additive Increase Multiplicative Decrease) adaptive
# concurrency control in the batch processor. The sim-model-aimd simulator
# starts with 100% failure injection, causing AIMD to drop concurrency to
# its floor. After clearing failures via the runtime admin API, AIMD
# recovers back to full capacity — all without pod restarts.
#
# Usage:
# 1. Deploy the dev cluster: make dev-deploy
# 2. Open Grafana: http://localhost:3000 → Processor dashboard → AIMD panels
# 3. Port-forward the simulator: kubectl port-forward svc/vllm-sim-aimd 8888:8000 -n default
# 4. Follow sequences below in order

# ============================================================
# CONFIGURATION
# ============================================================

@baseUrl = https://localhost:8000/v1
@tenantHeader = X-MaaS-Username
@tenantId = demo-user
@apiKey = unused
@inputFile = batch_input_aimd.jsonl
@namespace = default
@simAdminUrl = http://localhost:8888

# ============================================================
# SEQUENCE 1: Observe AIMD Drop Under Failures
# ============================================================
#
# The sim-model-aimd simulator is deployed with 100% rate_limit failure
# injection. All inference requests return 429, causing the AIMD controller
# to multiplicatively decrease the per-endpoint concurrency limit.
#
# Expected: concurrency drops from 10 → 5 (floor) within seconds.
# Watch the "AIMD Concurrency Limit per Endpoint" Grafana panel.

### Upload Batch Input File
# @name uploadFailure
POST {{baseUrl}}/files
{{tenantHeader}}: {{tenantId}}
Authorization: Bearer {{apiKey}}
Content-Type: multipart/form-data; boundary=----WebKitFormBoundary7MA4YWxkTrZu0gW

------WebKitFormBoundary7MA4YWxkTrZu0gW
Content-Disposition: form-data; name="purpose"

batch
------WebKitFormBoundary7MA4YWxkTrZu0gW
Content-Disposition: form-data; name="file"; filename="{{inputFile}}"
Content-Type: application/jsonl

< ./{{inputFile}}
------WebKitFormBoundary7MA4YWxkTrZu0gW--

# Set @fileId with the file ID from the response
@fileId =

### Create Batch (100% failures — AIMD will drop)
# @name createBatchFailure
POST {{baseUrl}}/batches
{{tenantHeader}}: {{tenantId}}
Authorization: Bearer {{apiKey}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "input_file_id": "{{fileId}}",
  "endpoint": "/v1/chat/completions",
  "completion_window": "24h"
}

# Set @batchId1 with the batch ID from the response
@batchId1 =

### Poll Batch Status
# Poll this while watching Grafana. The batch will eventually fail
# (all requests return 429). The important thing is the AIMD panel.
GET {{baseUrl}}/batches/{{batchId1}}
{{tenantHeader}}: {{tenantId}}
Authorization: Bearer {{apiKey}}

# ============================================================
# SEQUENCE 2: Clear Failures and Observe AIMD Recovery
# ============================================================
#
# Use the simulator's runtime admin API to disable failure injection,
# then submit a new batch. AIMD will additively increase concurrency
# back toward 10. No pod restart needed — the change is instant.
#
# Requires: kubectl port-forward svc/vllm-sim-aimd 8888:8000 -n default

### Get Current Simulator Config
GET {{simAdminUrl}}/admin/config
Accept: application/json

### Disable Failure Injection (instant — no pod restart)
POST {{simAdminUrl}}/admin/config
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "failure-injection-rate": 0
}

### Create Batch (0% failures — AIMD will recover)
# Reuses the same input file from Sequence 1.
# @name createBatchRecovery
POST {{baseUrl}}/batches
{{tenantHeader}}: {{tenantId}}
Authorization: Bearer {{apiKey}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "input_file_id": "{{fileId}}",
  "endpoint": "/v1/chat/completions",
  "completion_window": "24h"
}

# Set @batchId2 with the batch ID from the response
@batchId2 =

### Poll Batch Status (should complete successfully)
GET {{baseUrl}}/batches/{{batchId2}}
{{tenantHeader}}: {{tenantId}}
Authorization: Bearer {{apiKey}}

# Set @outputFileId2 with the output_file_id from the response
@outputFileId2 =

### Download Output File (when status = completed)
GET {{baseUrl}}/files/{{outputFileId2}}/content
{{tenantHeader}}: {{tenantId}}
Authorization: Bearer {{apiKey}}

# ============================================================
# SEQUENCE 3: Reset Simulator (restore 100% failures)
# ============================================================

### Restore 100% Failure Injection (for next demo run)
POST {{simAdminUrl}}/admin/config
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "failure-injection-rate": 100,
  "failure-types": ["rate_limit"]
}

# ============================================================
# MONITORING
# ============================================================

### Grafana — AIMD Panels
# Open in browser: http://localhost:3000/d/batch-gateway-processor
#
# Key panels:
#   - "AIMD Concurrency Limit per Endpoint" — shows the live limit per endpoint
#   - "AIMD Signals (decreases / increases)" — shows decrease/increase events by signal

### Query AIMD Concurrency Limit (Prometheus via Grafana)
GET http://localhost:3000/api/datasources/proxy/1/api/v1/query?query=batch_processor_aimd_concurrency_limit
Accept: application/json

### Query AIMD Decrease Signals (Prometheus via Grafana)
GET http://localhost:3000/api/datasources/proxy/1/api/v1/query?query=sum(rate(batch_processor_aimd_decreases_total[5m]))by(endpoint,signal)
Accept: application/json

### Query AIMD Increase Signals (Prometheus via Grafana)
GET http://localhost:3000/api/datasources/proxy/1/api/v1/query?query=sum(rate(batch_processor_aimd_increases_total[5m]))by(endpoint)
Accept: application/json

### Processor Metrics (Direct)
GET http://localhost:9090/metrics
Accept: text/plain

### Processor Health
GET http://localhost:9090/health
Accept: application/json
